In [10]:
# Handle Missing Data:
# delete rows with nan values? : all rows will be deteled!!
# strategy?
total = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
percent = (df.isnull().sum()/df.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)
missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 6))
plt.xticks(rotation='90')
sns.barplot(x=missing_data.index, y=missing_data['Percent'])
plt.xlabel('Features', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Percent of missing values', fontsize=15)
plt.title('Percent missing data by feature', fontsize=15)

#plot learning curves
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from mlxtend.plotting import plot_learning_curves
xgb = XGBRegressor()
X = df.drop("target", axis=1)
Y = df["target"]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)
    
plt.figure()
plot_learning_curves(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, xgb, print_model=False, style='ggplot')
plt.show()

from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(XGBRegressor(), 
                                                        X, 
                                                        Y,
                                                        # Number of folds in cross-validation
                                                        cv=10,
                                                        # Evaluation metric
                                                        scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error',
                                                        # Use all computer cores
                                                        n_jobs=2, 
                                                        # 50 different sizes of the training set
                                                        train_sizes=np.linspace(0.01, 1.0, 50))
In [31]:
# Create means and standard deviations of training set scores
train_mean = np.mean(-train_scores, axis=1)
train_std = np.std(-train_scores, axis=1)

# Create means and standard deviations of test set scores
test_mean = np.mean(-test_scores, axis=1)
test_std = np.std(-test_scores, axis=1)

# Draw lines
plt.plot(train_sizes, train_mean, '--', color="#111111",  label="Training score")
plt.plot(train_sizes, test_mean, color="#111111", label="Cross-validation score")

# Draw bands
plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_mean - train_std, train_mean + train_std, color="#DDDDDD")
plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_mean - test_std, test_mean + test_std, color="#DDDDDD")

# Create plot
plt.title("Learning Curve")
plt.xlabel("Training Set Size"), plt.ylabel("MAE Score"), plt.legend(loc="best")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Train and predict with each model
test_data_for_csv = pd.read_csv('data/test.csv')
results_test = pd.DataFrame(columns=['rmae_test', 'rmse_test'], index=model_name_list)
results_train = pd.DataFrame(columns=['rmae_train', 'rmse_train'], index=model_name_list)
    
for i, model in enumerate([model1, model2, model3, model4, model5, model6, model7, model8, model9, model10, model11, model12]):
       model.fit(X_train, y_train)
       y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
       y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)

       predictions = model.predict(test_data)
       submission_df = pd.DataFrame(
           {"uniqueid": test_data_for_csv["id"], "target": predictions})
       submission_df.to_csv("data/subs/"+str(model_name_list[i])+".csv", index=False)
        
       # Metrics on test set
       rmae_test = np.sqrt(np.mean(abs(y_pred_test - y_test)))
       rmse_test = np.sqrt(np.mean((y_pred_test - y_test) ** 2))


       # Metrics on train set
       rmae_train = np.sqrt(np.mean(abs(y_pred_train - y_train)))
       rmse_train = np.sqrt(np.mean((y_pred_train - y_train) ** 2))
       

       # Insert results into the dataframe
       model_name = model_name_list[i]
       results_test.loc[model_name, :] = [rmae_test, rmse_test]
       results_train.loc[model_name, :] = [rmae_train, rmse_train]
